## 📅 Day 26 - Swagger API Documentation

### 🚀 Overview

On Day 26, I implemented API documentation and testing using Swagger in my ASP.NET Core Web API project. This allows easy visualization, testing, and understanding of all available endpoints.

---

### 🔧 Features Implemented

* Integrated Swagger UI for API documentation
* Documented all CRUD endpoints (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
* Tested APIs directly using Swagger UI
* Configured JWT Authentication support in Swagger
* Enabled secure API testing using Bearer Token

---

### 🔐 Authentication Flow

* Implemented login endpoint to generate JWT token
* Used token-based authentication to secure APIs
* Added "Authorize" button in Swagger UI
* Passed token in format:

  ```
  Bearer <your_token>
  ```

---

### 🧪 API Testing

All endpoints were successfully tested using Swagger:

* ✅ Login (`/api/Auth/login`)
* ✅ Get All Employees (`GET /api/Employee`)
* ✅ Get Employee by ID (`GET /api/Employee/{id}`)
* ✅ Create Employee (`POST /api/Employee`)
* ✅ Update Employee (`PUT /api/Employee/{id}`)
* ✅ Delete Employee (`DELETE /api/Employee/{id}`)

---

### 🗄️ Database Integration

* Connected to SQL Server database
* Verified all CRUD operations reflect in database
* Used Entity Framework Core for ORM operations

---

### 📊 Logging & Middleware

* Implemented custom logging middleware to track requests
* Logs include:

  * Request start and end
  * API hits
  * Service layer operations
  * Database queries

---

### 🧠 Key Learnings

* Importance of API documentation
* How Swagger simplifies API testing
* Integration of JWT Authentication in Swagger
* Understanding request pipeline and middleware flow
* Real-time debugging using logs

---

### 💯 Outcome

Successfully built and tested a secure, documented REST API with full CRUD operations and authentication, making the project more professional and industry-ready.

